24
00:01:21,749 --> 00:01:24,930
okay, cool, just I'm counting on you to show up and know what you're doing.

25
00:01:25,590 --> 00:01:29,052
And so if this is terrible starting five minutes from now,

26
00:01:29,112 --> 00:01:30,332
then you have only yourselves to blame.

27
00:01:32,480 --> 00:01:33,506
So, I'm gonna go first.

28
00:01:34,561 --> 00:01:36,862
I'm Austin, I worked on some of these things,

29
00:01:37,843 --> 00:01:41,385
and my confession, of sorts,

30
00:01:42,065 --> 00:01:46,848
is that it turns out we have absolutely no control

31
00:01:47,528 --> 00:01:51,350
over our listeners slash audience slash players

32
00:01:51,491 --> 00:01:54,993
and what they are going to take away from our music.

33
00:01:55,793 --> 00:01:57,794
And so a shorter way of saying that

34
00:01:57,954 --> 00:02:01,136
is that we don't have the power of suggestion

35
00:02:01,176 --> 00:02:03,137
that we think we do as composers.

36
00:02:05,700 --> 00:02:14,542
So, when we're getting started in our careers and student work and that sort of thing, I

37
00:02:14,562 --> 00:02:20,083
think we spend a lot of time trying to really hone our craft with the goal of creating very

38
00:02:20,163 --> 00:02:22,964
specific emotional and visual responses.

39
00:02:23,724 --> 00:02:27,205
So in other words, we aspire to a very vivid and exact.

40
00:02:29,472 --> 00:02:31,653
images, feelings, etc. in the minds of our listeners.

41
00:02:31,693 --> 00:02:33,834
And I've been guilty of this, where I'll think to myself,

42
00:02:34,214 --> 00:02:37,016
because this music was written to evoke X,

43
00:02:37,636 --> 00:02:40,097
it therefore will forever universally evoke X.

44
00:02:40,537 --> 00:02:45,439
T-Rex versus the Hulk, in the most universal of musical images.

45
00:02:45,779 --> 00:02:47,940
But really, anything in front of you, it's like this water bottle.

46
00:02:48,320 --> 00:02:50,762
I was inspired by this water bottle.

47
00:02:50,802 --> 00:02:53,343
So theoretically, anybody listening for the future

48
00:02:53,363 --> 00:02:56,944
will just form water bottles in their head.

49
00:02:57,064 --> 00:02:58,685
Turns out, that's totally bullshit.

50
00:02:59,526 --> 00:03:01,628
should be obvious, this is why it's a confession.

51
00:03:03,049 --> 00:03:08,895
So, as an example, on Journey, I was aspiring to,

52
00:03:09,435 --> 00:03:11,037
by the time you reach the end of the game,

53
00:03:11,097 --> 00:03:14,700
something that I would call sweeping or soaring,

54
00:03:14,740 --> 00:03:17,963
or if I'm feeling daring, I would want it to feel

55
00:03:18,164 --> 00:03:19,825
exhilarating or even spiritual,

56
00:03:19,885 --> 00:03:21,747
and so this particular excerpt.

57
00:03:33,554 --> 00:03:36,536
Baba, okay. So, actual response.

58
00:03:37,736 --> 00:03:40,538
Stunning music. It really reminds me of Metal Gear Solid's soundtrack,

59
00:03:40,578 --> 00:03:41,858
Here's to You. You should check it out.

60
00:03:43,559 --> 00:03:44,780
So, I did check it out.

61
