00:07:16,887 --> 00:07:18,009
Truth is, I probably would.

120
00:07:18,369 --> 00:07:19,390
Big fan of Bioshock.

121
00:07:20,192 --> 00:07:21,333
So flash forward.

122
00:07:22,244 --> 00:07:23,264
I thought I'd learned this lesson.

123
00:07:23,324 --> 00:07:26,726
After many years of the sort of incorrect compliments,

124
00:07:27,626 --> 00:07:29,567
I think I probably internalized that a little too much.

125
00:07:29,627 --> 00:07:30,907
So when it came time to do Abzu,

126
00:07:32,588 --> 00:07:35,148
both probably because I probably internalized

127
00:07:35,168 --> 00:07:36,289
some of that Journey feedback too much,

128
00:07:36,329 --> 00:07:38,490
but also because, earnestly, the game had a very,

129
00:07:38,550 --> 00:07:39,870
very different sort of energy to it,

130
00:07:39,970 --> 00:07:41,511
very kinetic, very full of life.

131
00:07:42,171 --> 00:07:44,292
So I said, okay, I want to be very emotionally,

132
00:07:44,552 --> 00:07:47,753
I accepted, apparently, Journey is tranquil and meditative,

133
00:07:48,733 --> 00:07:50,194
and now I don't want to do that.

134
00:07:50,274 --> 00:07:51,554
Now I want to be very melodic.

135
00:07:52,615 --> 00:07:56,459
not meditative at all, really match the kinetic energy of the game.

136
00:07:57,019 --> 00:08:00,022
And I want to pretend that's not because of this feedback from Journey,

137
00:08:00,042 --> 00:08:01,483
but it probably made its way in there a bit.

138
00:08:01,503 --> 00:08:04,005
So here's an example of me not being meditative

139
00:08:04,426 --> 00:08:07,829
and trying to be more overtly melodic.

140
00:08:24,933 --> 00:08:28,257
Okay, blah blah blah.

141
00:08:28,297 --> 00:08:36,865
So after getting about 50 of these, apparently it sounds exactly like Tomb Raider or Tom

142
00:08:36,925 --> 00:08:37,165
Raider.

143
00:08:37,185 --> 00:08:42,790
That's Tom Salta's pet project, I guess.

144
00:08:44,625 --> 00:08:48,870
Should have seen some of that coming, although I honestly had not played Tomb Raider since

145
00:08:49,631 --> 00:08:53,095
it came out 20 years ago, and I went back and was one of those like, motherfucker, I

146
00:08:53,135 --> 00:08:56,119
can actually hear why people are saying that.

147
00:08:57,280 --> 00:09:03,968
So after wading through all of those, here's a review I found on Amazon, and if you look

148
00:09:03,988 --> 00:09:04,489
at the bottom.

149
00:09:05,873 --> 00:09:10,354
They say, this score seems overly intellectual instead of from the heart.

150
00:09:10,795 --> 00:09:14,295
I find the music lines lose me as a listener in the same way.

151
00:09:14,555 --> 00:09:16,756
What I'm trying to say is, I feel lost.

152
00:09:17,456 --> 00:09:21,717
I feel I get lost listening to his newer scores without being able to remember the melodies.

153
00:09:21,757 --> 00:09:24,798
Go back and listen to Flow or Journey and you cannot forget the tunes.

154
00:09:25,798 --> 00:09:33,039
So somehow the less melodic, more meditative score is more melodic than the explicitly

155
00:09:33,139 --> 00:09:34,680
trying to be melodic score.

156
00:09:37,703 --> 00:09:44,567
At least Flo is on the list, which is especially bizarre and helps me try to let it go, because

157
00:09:44,687 --> 00:09:46,548
Flo is just overtly not melodic.

158
00:09:46,608 --> 00:09:49,390
Anyone who says so, I just don't even know where they're coming from.

159
00:09:50,530 --> 00:09:55,353
And this was probably the true culmination, is literal side-by-side comments.

160
00:09:55,833 --> 00:09:56,894
Very disappointing.

161
00:09:57,935 --> 00:09:59,515
It's lacking strong musical ideas.

162
00:09:59,575 --> 00:10:01,036
It sounds intellectual and not from the heart.

163
00:10:01,076 --> 00:10:02,397
I think that might be the same person.

164
00:10:04,048 --> 00:10:08,149
And then immediately below it, I'm crying piles of tears and all this sort of...

165
00:10:08,489 --> 00:10:16,170
So I'm sitting here looking at this, and it dawns on me that it's possible to simultaneously

166
00:10:16,310 --> 00:10:17,510
fail and succeed.

167
00:10:18,890 --> 00:10:23,111
And that was something I had never thought about before, considered possible.

168
00:10:23,651 --> 00:10:31,053
So the bottom line is, when getting into the creative zone and the process, the big confession

169
00:10:31,093 --> 00:10:31,593
was that I...

170
00:10:32,880 --> 00:10:36,065
try to let go of the whole outside world while writing.

171
00:10:36,106 --> 00:10:37,748
But then as soon as the writing is done,

172
00:10:37,768 --> 00:10:41,896
I turn into this monster that's scouring the world

173
00:10:41,956 --> 00:10:44,440
to see if I succeeded in my goal.

174
00:10:45,141 --> 00:10:46,664
Did I actually create?

175
00:10:47,802 --> 00:10:51,222
what I thought I created based on what people are saying about it.

176
00:10:51,683 --> 00:10:55,484
And the confession really is that no good comes of this.

177
00:10:55,824 --> 00:10:57,224
This is not a healthy practice.

178
00:10:57,764 --> 00:10:59,465
We can't control what people are going to think.

179
00:10:59,605 --> 00:11:01,685
We can't control what their takeaway would be.

180
00:11:01,785 --> 00:11:04,886
As my father used to say, you would worry a lot less what other people think if you

181
00:11:04,926 --> 00:11:06,226
realized how infrequently they do.

182
00:11:08,708 --> 00:11:13,469
Actually, I said that wrong and made it sound extremely asshole-ish.

183
00:11:13,509 --> 00:11:18,010
You would worry a lot less what people think of you if you realized how infrequently they

184
00:11:18,050 --> 00:11:18,210
do.

185
00:11:21,070 --> 00:11:25,812
So basically, the bottom line is we should be grateful that anyone is listening at all

186
00:11:26,452 --> 00:11:30,653
and extremely grateful if they like it and then just accept everything else.

