517
00:23:32,916 --> 00:23:35,019
I made in my early approach to orchestration,

518
00:23:35,560 --> 00:23:37,863
how I learned from them, and how I've applied this knowledge

519
00:23:37,884 --> 00:23:38,905
to all my writing since then.

520
00:23:41,247 --> 00:23:45,369
I'd written several indie game scores before working at Lucas, but The Old Republic was

521
00:23:45,389 --> 00:23:49,090
the first time I had a AAA score and my first time writing for live orchestra.

522
00:23:49,530 --> 00:23:55,853
We had a very tight deadline, and so it was also my first time writing extensively for

523
00:23:55,893 --> 00:23:59,094
Star Wars, so there was a lot of pressure to get the John Williams sound right.

524
00:24:02,138 --> 00:24:06,622
I used high quality samples for the mockups and my cues were approved, so conceptually

525
00:24:06,642 --> 00:24:07,403
the music worked well.

526
00:24:07,983 --> 00:24:13,288
But I never had the experience of going from mockup to live orchestra, and I had no idea

527
00:24:13,428 --> 00:24:15,490
of the headaches that these cues would cause.

528
00:24:16,010 --> 00:24:20,214
I wrote for the sound, not for the players, and so I was in for a rude awakening.

529
00:24:22,635 --> 00:24:25,979
We had four other composers and a ton of music to get through in a short time.

530
00:24:26,659 --> 00:24:28,581
Some of my cues were played effortlessly,

531
00:24:28,701 --> 00:24:30,923
with musicians reading beautifully on their first try.

532
00:24:31,344 --> 00:24:35,828
But others, easy pieces left them confused and grumpy and dissatisfied.

533
00:24:36,309 --> 00:24:37,410
So here's a few reasons why.

534
00:24:40,052 --> 00:24:42,775
My first problem was writing parts with awkward entrances

535
00:24:42,875 --> 00:24:44,657
and needlessly unnatural rhythms.

536
00:24:45,625 --> 00:24:47,947
players would have to count several measures of rest

537
00:24:47,987 --> 00:24:50,728
before oddly timed entrances with no obvious backing.

538
00:24:51,348 --> 00:24:53,810
And this led to very unconfident performances

539
00:24:53,850 --> 00:24:55,091
and unnecessary retakes.

540
00:24:58,873 --> 00:25:00,614
I had some cues, like you see here.

541
00:25:03,095 --> 00:25:04,055
This is real, by the way.

542
00:25:04,095 --> 00:25:04,896
This is not made up.

543
00:25:06,101 --> 00:25:08,743
Some cues for instruments just had very inconsequential parts,

544
00:25:08,963 --> 00:25:11,465
writing half the piece just to play only a short passage.

545
00:25:12,225 --> 00:25:14,787
Again, this was because I focused only on the sound

546
00:25:15,107 --> 00:25:16,969
and not on the performance or the players.

547
00:25:21,272 --> 00:25:23,834
And I had some generally dissatisfying parts as well, which.

548
00:25:24,863 --> 00:25:28,245
Yeah, which sounded great in samples, but didn't work when played live.

549
00:25:29,046 --> 00:25:32,128
In this instance, as you see, the harp just plays a single tremolo throughout the whole

550
00:25:32,208 --> 00:25:32,508
cue.

551
00:25:32,928 --> 00:25:37,451
And it was a great texture for the ice planet Hoth, but in practice it was very boring and

552
00:25:37,491 --> 00:25:42,034
very static, and honestly just unacceptable to give to a professional player who'd studied

553
00:25:42,074 --> 00:25:42,655
their whole life.

554
00:25:45,897 --> 00:25:46,477
Speaking of harp...

555
00:25:50,850 --> 00:25:55,273
So harpists play accidentals via pedals that transpose all notes of a kind.

556
00:25:55,973 --> 00:25:58,674
Here I tried a harmonic shift between two hexatonic modes,

557
00:25:58,694 --> 00:26:00,315
which is a very Star Wars-y technique.

558
00:26:00,875 --> 00:26:03,677
But unfortunately, this required six pedal changes at once.

559
00:26:04,437 --> 00:26:13,822
And most harpists only have two feet, so it was actually impossible to play.

560
00:26:19,838 --> 00:26:23,242
And lastly, I had some cues that I just simply didn't proofread closely enough

561
00:26:23,282 --> 00:26:25,024
when I got them back from our orchestration team.

562
00:26:25,885 --> 00:26:27,767
One piece had incorrect dynamics at the end,

563
00:26:27,867 --> 00:26:30,289
turning an ambient piece unexpectedly violent.

564
00:26:33,593 --> 00:26:35,515
And another just had very glitched rhythms

565
00:26:35,615 --> 00:26:39,098
where we had to fix it at the podium, which is a huge time waste.

566
00:26:42,130 --> 00:26:46,096
I learned from these mistakes and studied other scores with a focus on performance.

567
00:26:46,797 --> 00:26:51,003
Before my next score for Star Wars First Assault, I developed strategies to make sure that the

568
00:26:51,043 --> 00:26:53,747
parts were playable, sight-readable, and enjoyable.

569
00:26:54,327 --> 00:26:55,269
Here's some of those techniques.

570
00:26:58,158 --> 00:27:01,681
The first principle I followed was to just make sure everyone has at least something

571
00:27:01,801 --> 00:27:03,563
interesting to do in each cue.

572
00:27:04,343 --> 00:27:08,427
Previously, I might have allowed a harp part to be nothing but glisses for an entire cue,

573
00:27:08,467 --> 00:27:12,710
but in this example, I made sure that they had some melodic doubling to keep things interesting.

574
00:27:16,288 --> 00:27:19,131
Avoid writing awkward entrances at all costs.

575
00:27:19,391 --> 00:27:21,573
These again can lead to unconfident performances.

576
00:27:22,293 --> 00:27:23,634
If you need arrhythmic elements,

577
00:27:24,174 --> 00:27:26,076
a neat trick to try is write it in 4-4,

578
00:27:26,236 --> 00:27:27,857
but use tuplets or syncopation.

579
00:27:28,658 --> 00:27:30,479
Here the strings have scattered entrances,

580
00:27:30,559 --> 00:27:31,960
but it's easy to count in 4-4,

581
00:27:32,361 --> 00:27:33,542
especially with the harp doubling.

582
00:27:37,525 --> 00:27:40,727
Make sure brass isn't being abused with constant fortissimo.

583
00:27:42,104 --> 00:27:43,566
Horns especially need time to rest,

584
00:27:43,767 --> 00:27:46,311
particularly if you need them to make a big entrance later on.

585
00:27:46,852 --> 00:27:49,276
So in this example, from Laura Croft actually,

586
00:27:50,037 --> 00:27:51,900
I remove them from the text here at measure eight

587
00:27:52,421 --> 00:27:54,223
using a trombone to support the trumpet

588
00:27:54,263 --> 00:27:56,407
so that the horns can come in full force later on.

589
00:28:00,515 --> 00:28:05,279
Try writing in fun challenges that sound more difficult than they actually are, showcasing

590
00:28:05,319 --> 00:28:06,240
the player's versatility.

591
00:28:06,760 --> 00:28:11,745
A good habit is to study instrumental etudes to get to know what's guaranteed to be mastered

592
00:28:11,765 --> 00:28:12,465
by a professional.

593
00:28:13,386 --> 00:28:17,470
For example, these wind runs and arpeggio... arpeggiando violas.

594
00:28:20,052 --> 00:28:22,895
Try using cues to provide alternate textural options.

595
00:28:23,634 --> 00:28:26,818
When recording, you can easily adjust dynamics or tacit instruments,

596
00:28:27,179 --> 00:28:28,781
but you can't really add new parts.

597
00:28:29,502 --> 00:28:32,246
Using cues allows you to thicken the textures if necessary.

598
00:28:32,687 --> 00:28:35,111
For example, expanding a solo to a full section.

599
00:28:39,034 --> 00:28:41,155
We should take into account not just the performance,

600
00:28:41,195 --> 00:28:42,095
but also the venue.

601
00:28:42,755 --> 00:28:44,576
For Star Wars First Assault, we were at Abbey Road,

602
00:28:44,616 --> 00:28:46,577
which is big enough to seat an entire orchestra

603
00:28:46,597 --> 00:28:48,078
in two different configurations.

604
00:28:48,858 --> 00:28:50,018
We had two factions in the game,

605
00:28:50,078 --> 00:28:52,279
so we recorded Imperial music in portrait

606
00:28:52,459 --> 00:28:53,700
and Rebel music in landscape.

607
00:28:57,465 --> 00:29:02,266
So to wrap things up, the most important thing is to talk to musicians about any questionable

608
00:29:02,286 --> 00:29:02,587
parts.

609
00:29:03,207 --> 00:29:08,089
Ideally, befriend someone from every section and get their feedback for whatever you're

610
00:29:08,129 --> 00:29:11,110
not comfortable with before it hits the copyist.

611
00:29:11,530 --> 00:29:12,590
Their input isn't valuable.

612
00:29:15,673 --> 00:29:18,836
